Pre-processing data tables for SC-ION

  1. Download the SC-ION repository from Github. Unzip the folder and save it to an accessible location on your computer. Also unzip the TEST.zip folder within as it contains the normalized data tables and processing script for this step

  2. Prior to running SC-ION, process the output tables within the TEST folder by running the R utility script create_data_tables.R. The output files will be used in the next step.

Running the SC-ION RShiny Application

  1. Open RStudio and use setwd() to change the working directory to the folder containing the SC-ION scripts.

  2. Start the app by running the START_SCION.R script, either by entering source(START_SCION.R) into the R Console or by clicking the “Run App” button in the top right corner with the green arrow. A new window will open containing the SC-ION app interface.

  3. First, build the TF protein abundance network using the input files and parameters shown in Figure 1a. A number of files and folders will be produced; this includes FINAL_NETWORK.txt which combines individual networks for each cluster. Save these files to a new folder (e.g. TF-protein-network).

  4. Repeat step 5 to build the TF phosphosite network as shown in Figure 1b. This will create another set of files and folders which should be saved to a new folder (e.g. TF-phosphosite-network).

Figure 1. SC-ION network inference on protein abundance (a) and phosphosite (b) data. Important parameter differences between the two data types are highlighted with blue boxes.

Tips and Tricks

  1. The TEST.zip folder contains the following files: 1) JA_FPKM.csv which contains the normalized transcriptome (target) data; 2) Normalized_values_protein.csv and Normalized_values_phospho.csv which contain the normalized protein abundance and phosphosite (regulator) data; and 3) SCION_candidates.txt which contains the list of candidate genes for this example.

  2. The create_data_tables.R script may be altered to read in different input files for future uses of SC-ION with other datasets.

  3. In the create_data_tables.R script, make sure to change the working directory in setwd() (line 6) to the directory containing the normalized tables.

  4. The utility script create_data_tables.R performs the following steps: 1) builds the target matrix using the candidate/target list and target data; 2) builds the regulator matrix; 3) extracts the list of regulators (in this example, TFs) from the regulator matrix; and 4) builds the clustering matrix. Phosphosite information is retained in the phosphosite regulator and target tables so that SC-ION may infer regulatory edges at the site level.

  5. Currently, SC-ION only supports comma-separated value (.csv) files. SC-ION may support more file types in the future.

  6. SC-ION produces a number of output files: 1) cluster.csv which contains the clustering results; 2) a folder called Cluster networks which contains individual networks for each cluster; and 3) FINAL_NETWORK.txt file where individual networks for each cluster are combined into a single file. FINAL_NETWORK.txt can be imported into Cytoscape for visualization.

  7. Clustering is optional; if omitted, only a FINAL_NETWORK.txt file will be created.

  8. Output files will be overwritten every time SC-ION is run, so make sure to rename the output files after each run.
